Overprint settings enable you to apply additional graphic elements to the pages, the composition of which depends on conditions which may only occur during the output management phase. 

For example, you may apply wording indicating the position of each page in relation to the start of the Shipment or the Spool Set.To do this, the overprint settings use a graphical editor similar to the one used in the Contents view, instructions for which can be found in the User Manual.

You may create more than one Overprint configuration for each Serializer. During print spool generation, only four of these may be used at any one time. For each configuration, you may set the Overprint for the whole print job (i.e. for each page produced) or set a different procedure for each Processing Lot.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Creating an overprint setting
- In the **Output settings **exploration panel, click on New.

- Click **Overprint Settings...**.

- Enter a code for the setting in the **New overprint settings **window.

- If a serializer was selected when **Overprint Settings... **was clicked, it will be displayed in the **New overprint settings **window in the Serializer menu; otherwise, the menu will be empty. Select the Serializer required.

- Click **New **or press **Enter **to confirm the creation and close the window.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Warning

The Overprint setting creation window performs a validation on the code entered. If the value used is the same as another code in the Serializer, creation is not possible.

## Changing the code of an overprint setting
- In the **Output settings **exploration panel, click on **Overprint**.

- Click **Change **beside the code on the line corresponding to the settings whose code you wish to change.

- Enter your code of choice in the **Change overprint setting **window.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Click **Apply **to confirm the change and close the window.

> Warning

The Overprint setting modification window performs a validation on the code entered. If the field is empty or the value used is the same as another identifier in the Serializer, modification is not possible.

## Changing the name of an overprint setting
- In the **Output settings **exploration panel, click on **Overprint**.

- Click the line corresponding to the setting whose code you wish to change.

- Double click the name of the setting to access edit mode.

- Change the name and click **Enter **to confirm.

> Tip

If you have more than one configuration, press [tab] to move from one setting to another without losing the modification mode.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Deleting an overprint setting

- In the **Output settings **exploration panel, click on **Overprint**.

- Click the line corresponding to the overprint setting you wish to delete.

- Click **Delete...**.

- In the confirmation prompt window, click **Delete **to confirm the operation and close the window.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## **Graphic operations**
### Accessing the graphic operations of an overprint setting
- In the **Output settings **exploration panel, click on the name of the Overprint setting you wish to access.

- Select the type required from the **Type **menu. This will give you access to the ***Print Job ***type which applies settings to all the pages produced, and a type for each Processing Lot which applies configurations only to the pages in the lot concerned.

- Select the category of sheets with which you wish to associate the overprint from the **Apply on **menu

> Note

The menu depends on the selected Type and may contain some of the following values:

**all sheets of document**

- **first sheet of each document **

- **last sheet of each document **

- **every sheet of the envelope **

- **first sheet of the envelope **

- **last sheet of the envelope **

- **spool file header**

- **spool file trailer **

- **skipped page**

- Select the side of the sheet to be configured from the **Side **menu.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Graphics operations on an overprint
All graphic operations on overprint management require the configuration of choice to be accessed as described in the *Accessing the graphic operations of an overprint setting *section above.

Graphic operations are carried out by means of a graphic editor similar to the one used for Resources Management, which offers the following features:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Enters a line element.

> Note

For more information, see: 2 - Line

**Simple Text**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Enters a simple text element in placeholder mode. 

> Note

For more information, see: 3 - Simple Text.

**barset**

### Inserting a barset
Click ![](data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAABAAAAAOCAIAAACpTQvdAAAABmJLR0QA/wD/AP+gvaeTAAAACXBIWXMAAA7EAAAOxAGVKw4bAAAAVElEQVQoke2PoRGAQBADL9mjDDTM0A010CEGi33/Ak0jGAr4dwjik81qXrfoSUbEMo02WIIUhgTAgA227CGx9+N01/xLqNfdXlAppYugX7rx0sekH42HGC32UF9tAAAAAElFTkSuQmCC) to insert a barset.

### Editing the properties of a barset
- Click on the barset element that you wish to edit to select it.

- Select the **Barset **tab.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Enter the value required for the **Bars distance**.

- Enter the value required for the **Bar thickness**.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Assigning variable data to a barset
- Click the element of the barset to which you wish to add variable data to select it.

- In the **Data **panel, open the **System **tab.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Locate the attribute required using the procedures described in the *Finding attributes *section.

- Select the attribute confirming with the ![](data:image/png;base64,) icon.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- It is possible to drag the attribute in the panel below.

- If there are more attributes, it will be possible to drag the attribute up or down in the panel to change its position.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Warning

The barset shows one bar for every attribute assigned. Boolean Attributes have to be used to assign variable data to the barset. During print spool generation, the value of each Boolean Attribute will decide whether or not the corresponding bar is present.

### Deleting variable data from a barset
- Click the element of the barset from which you wish to delete variable data to select it.

- In **Attributes management** panel select the attribute you wish to delete.

- Click on the **Delete **icon  ![](data:image/png;base64,) to delete the attribute.

> Warning

When an attribute is deleted, a bar will be removed from the barset.

### Changing the order of the attributes in a barset
- Click on the element of the barset which you wish to rearrange the attributes of.

- In the variable data assigned panel, click on the attribute name you wish to move.

- Drag the attribute, remaining within the panel of the variable data assigned, and release it in the position required.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

### Modifying the rotation of an element
- Click the element whose rotation you wish to change to select it.

- Select the **Size **tab.

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

- Click  ![](data:image/png;base64,)	to increase rotation by 90. 

Or:

Click ![](data:image/png;base64,)  to reduce rotation by 90.

> Warning

The rotation of elements is not shown in the graphic editor.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

### Managing layers
Layer Management allows you to add new layers over the usual background. Layers are applied on a specific event, defined by the **Type **and **Apply on **settings.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Renam e layer**

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)
